Horse meat in British burgers
Daging kuda di burger Inggris
Germany decides fate of Cold War gold
Jerman memutuskan nasib emas Perang Dingin

Food standards officers are investigating how horse meat got into beef burgers on sale in Britain and the Irish Republic.
Irish food safety officials found traces of horse -- and pig -- DNA in ten products, sold by several food suppliers as beef throughout the two countries.
Horse meat poses no health risks, but in the British isles there is a cultural aversion to eating it.
One of Britain's leading supermarkets, Tesco, has apologised to customers after tests found that one burger contained almost one-third horse meat.
Para petugas pengawas makanan menyelidiki bagaimana daging kuda bercampur dengan burger daging sapi yang dijual di Inggris dan Republik Irlandia.
Para pejabat keamanan makanan menemukan jejak-jejak DNA kuda dan babi di 10 produk, yang dijual sebagai burger daging sapi oleh sejumlah pemasok makanan di kedua negara.
Daging kuda tidak menimbulkan risiko kesehatan, tetapi ada budaya untuk tidak mengkonsumsi daging kuda di pulau-pulau kecil Inggris.
Salah satu supermarket terbesar di Inggris, Tesco, telah meminta maaf kepada konsumen setelah pemeriksaan menunjukkan bahwa di dalam satu burger terdapat hampir sepertiga daging kuda.

Germany's central bank, the Bundesbank, is expected to announce today (Wednesday) that it will repatriate most of the gold bullion it sent to vaults abroad for safety during the Cold War.
Two-thirds of the gold reserves, worth about US$120 billion dollars, were sent to France, Britain, and the United States, because of fears they would be captured in the event of a Soviet invasion.
German federal auditors have criticised the government for not being certain of just how much gold there is or whether all the bars are genuine.
Bank sentral Jerman, Bundesbank, hari ini (Rabu) dijadwalkan mengumumkan akan memulangkan sebagian besar emas lantakan yang disimpan di brangkas-brangkas luar negeri selama Perang Dingin.
Dua pertiga cadangan emas, yang bernilai sekitar US$120 miliar dolar, dikirim ke Prancis, Inggris dan Amerika Serikat, karena dikhawatirkan emas tersebut akan disita bila terjadi invasi Soviet.
Auditur federal Jerman mengkritik pemerintah karena tidak yakin berapa jumlah emas yang ada atau apakah semua batangannya asli.
