Netherlands repeals blasphemy law
Belanda cabut UU penghujatan agama
Australian police break up credit card theft ring in Romania
Polisi Australia membongkar jaringan pencurian kartu kredit di Romania

Parliament in the Netherlands has agreed to repeal a law making it a crime to insult God. A majority of parties who supported the motion said the country no longer needed the law.
The limits of freedom of speech in the Netherlands were put to the test last year in trial of far-right politician Geert Wilders, when judges ruled he had the right to criticise Islam, even if his opinions were insulting to many Muslims.
It still remains illegal under Dutch law to insult police officers or Queen Beatrix, the country's monarch.
Parlemen Belanda sepakat untuk mencabut undang-undang yang menjadikan menghina Tuhan sebagai kejahatan.
Mayoritas partai di Belanda mendukung langkah itu dan menyatakan Belanda tidak lagi memerlukan UU itu.
Kebebasan berpendapat di Belanda diuji tahun lalu dengan pengadilan politisi sayap kanan Geert Wilders. Para hakim saat itu mengatakan ia memiliki hak untuk mengkritik Islam, walaupun pendapatnya menghina umat Islam.
Berdasarkan UU Belanda, menghina polisi atau Ratu Beatrix merupakan hal ilegal.

International police forces have broken up a Romanian syndicate allegedly responsible for the biggest ever credit card data theft in Australia. 
Seven people were charged in Romania with stealing details of 30,000 credit cards used for buying goods from around the world worth over US$30 juta.
The Australian Federal Police say that computer systems of 100 small businesses in Australia were hacked.
Pasukan polisi internasional membongkar sindikat Rumania yang diduga berada di balik pencurian terbesar data kartu kredit di Australia.
Tujuh orang di dakwa di Rumania dengan tuduhan mencuri rincian 30.000 kartu kredit dan digunakan untuk membeli barang-barang dari seluruh dunia senilai lebih dari US$30 juta.
Polisi Federal Australia mengatakan sistem komputer sekitar 100 usaha kecil di Australia dibobol.
