Seal flu virus 'could jump to humans'
Virus flu singa laut 'dapat menular ke manusia'
India hit by power cut second day running

Scientists in the United States have identified a new strain of flu which they say could pose a threat to human health.
H3N8 has been associated with the deaths of seals in New England. It's thought to have evolved from a type circulating in birds, and may be the first example of a virus crossing species from birds to marine mammals.
The scientists, writing in the journal of the American Society for Microbiology, say the mutation means H3N8 also has the ability to target the human respiratory tract.
Para ilmuwan di Amerika Serikat menemukan flu jenis baru yang mereka katakan dapat mengancam kesehatan manusia.
H3N8 dikaitkan dengan kematian singa-singa laut di New England. Virus ini diperkirakan berkembang dari jenis yang menyebar pada burung dan mungkin merupakan contoh pertama virus yang melintas spesies dari burung ke mamalia laut.
Para ilmuwan, yang menulis di jurnal Masyarakat Amerika untuk Mikrobiologi, mengatakan dengan mutasi itu berarti H3N8 juga dapat mempengaruhi sistem pernafasan manusia.

Officials in India say the electricity grid in the north of the country has failed for a second day. 
On Monday more than 370 million across the north of the country were affected by the loss of power, bringing the capital, Delhi, to a standstill.
The Indian news agency, Press Trust of India, says the eastern grid has also failed.
Para pejabat di India mengatakan pasok listrik di utara negara itu masih terganggu untuk hari kedua.
Hari Senin, lebih dari 370 juta orang di seluruh kawasan utara negara itu terganggu padam listrik, dan menyebabkan ibukota Delhi, lumpuh.
Kantor berita India, Press Trust of India, mengatakan jaringan listrik di kawasan timur juga mati.
