Former South Korean leader's daughter contests presidency
Anak perempuan eks presiden Korsel ikut pilpres
Contraception could save 100.000 lives
Kontrasepsi bisa selamatkan 100.000 jiwa

The daughter of a late military-backed president of South Korea has officially launched her attempt to become the country's first female leader.
Park Geun-hye, of the governing conservative Saenuri Party, promised that if elected, she would work for a fair economy, expand welfare and improve relations with North Korea.
Her father, Park Chung-hee, led South Korea's economic recovery in the 1960s and 70s but was seen by many as a military dictator.
He was shot dead by his spy chief in 1979.
Putri mendiang presiden Korea Selatan dukungan militer secara resmi memulai upaya menjadi pemimpin perempuan pertama negara tersebut.
Park Geun-hye dari Partai Saenuri, partai konservatif yang berkuasa, berjanji jika terpilih ia akan menerapkan kebijakan ekonomi yang lebih adil, meningkatkan kesejahteraan, dan memperbaiki hubungan dengan Korea Utara.
Ayahnya, Park Chung-hee, memimpin pemulihan ekonomi Korea Selatan pada 1960-an dan 1970-an namun dipandang oleh banyak kalangan sebagai diktator militer.
Ia tewas ditembak oleh kepala badan intelijen pada 1979.

Greater access to contraception could reduce the annual global figure for maternal deaths. 
Researchers in the United States say that around one-hundred-thousand lives could be saved every year around the world if contraception was distributed to all couples who want it.
According to a study published in the British medical journal, The Lancet, greater access to contraception could reduce the annual global figure for maternal deaths by almost a third.
The researchers say it would mainly benefit women in developing countries who suffer complications from pregnancy or abortion.
Para peneliti di Amerika Serikat mengatakan bahwa sekitar 100.000 jiwa bisa diselamatan setiap tahun di seluruh dunia jika kontrasepsi dibagikan ke semua pasangan yang membutuhkan.
Menurut kajian yang diterbitkan jurnal kedokteran Inggris, The Lancet, akses kontrasepsi yang lebih besar bisa memangkas angka global tahunan kematian ibu hingga hampir sepertiga.
Para peneliti mengatakan kontrasepsi akan bermanfaat terutama untuk kalangan perempuan di negara-negara berkembang yang mengalami komplikasi ketika hamil atau saat aborsi.
