Sony to cut 10,000 jobs
Sony akan mem-PHK 10.000 karyawan
Elephant poaching on the rise
Perburuan gajah meningkat

Sony has been struggling to compete against rivals like Samsung in the TV business.
The Japanese electronics giant, Sony, says it will cut about ten-thousand jobs - or six percent of its workforce - as it struggles to tackle big losses.
The firm says the posts will go around the world over the next twelve months.
On Tuesday Sony doubled an estimate of its expected losses this year - to six-point-four billion dollars.
The company has been struggling to compete against rivals like Samsung in the television business and Apple in the audio and mobile phone markets.
Raksasa elektronik Jepang, Sony, mengatakan mereka akan merumahkan sekitar 10.000 karyawan -atau 6% dari total pegawai- di saat perusahaan kesulitan mengatasi dampak kerugian besar.
Sony mengatakan PHK karyawan dilakukan di seluruh dunia dalam 12 bulan mendatang.
Pada hari Selasa Sony mengumumkan perkiraan kerugian yang akan naik dua kali lipat, menjadi US$6,4 miliar.
Perusahaan ini dalam beberapa waktu terakhir kesulitan bersaing dengan kompetitor seperti Samsung di bisnis televisi dan Apple di pasar audio dan telepon genggam.

Samburu in Kenya has lost more than a quarter of its elephants over the past three years. 
A BBC investigation suggests that elephant poaching is on the rise despite an international ban on the trade in ivory.
Just one Kenyan district, Samburu, has lost more than a quarter of its elephants over the past three years.
A BBC correspondent says the situation changed after four southern African countries were four years ago allowed to sell stockpiled ivory to China and Japan legally.
He adds the illegal trade is also driven by demand from this market.
Investigasi BBC menunjukkan perburuan gajah meningkat meski diterapkan larangan internasional perdagangan gading gajah.
Di satu distrik di Kenya saja, di Samburu, populasi gajah menurun hingga lebih 75% dalam tiga tahun terakhir.
Wartawan BBC mengatakan situasinya berubah setelah empat negara di Afrika selatan diizinkan menjual persediaan gading gajah ke Cina dan Jepang empat tahun silam.
Ia menambahkan perdagangan ilegal gading gajah juga didorong permintaan dari pasar tersebut.
