Italian police seize 'mafia companies'
Polisi Italia sita 'perusahaan mafia'
Afghan bank heads jailed
Dua direktur Kabul Bank dipenjara

Police in Italy say they've made 20 arrests and seized assets worth hundreds of millions of dollars in an operation against a mafia network operating in the tourist industry in the south of the country.
Those detained face charges of money laundering.
The assets seized include companies and holiday villages along the southern coast of Calabria.
Among those arrested were two Spaniards and a British man.
Polisi di Italia mengatakan mereka menangkap 20 orang dan menyita aset bernilai ratusan juta dolar dalam operasi membongkar jaringan mafia di industri pariwisata di Italia selatan.
Mereka yang ditangkap menghadapi dakwaan pencucian uang.
Aset-aset yang disita mencakup sejumlah perusahaan dan desa-desa wisata di sepanjang kawasan pantai Calabria.
Di antara yang ditangkap adalah dua warga Spanyol dan seorang pria Inggris.



The two top executives of Kabul Bank have been sentenced to five years in prison following its collapse, which threatened the entire Afghan economy.
The men were also ordered to pay back hundreds of millions of dollars they stole.
One anti-corruption group described the sentences as relatively light given the nature of the crime.
Kabul Bank was Afghanistan's largest private financial institution that handled the payments of many public servants.
Dua direktur Kabul Bank dijatuhi hukuman penjara lima tahun menyusul ambruknya bank tersebut, yang mengancam perekonomian Afghanistan.
Keduanya juga diperintahkan mengembalikan ratusan juta dolar uang yang mereka curi.
Satu kelompok antikorupsi menggambarkan vonis ini relatif ringan dibandingkan dengan kejahatan yang mereka lakukan.
Kabul Bank dikenal sebagai lembaga keuangan swasta terbesar di Afghanistan dan antara lain bertanggung jawab atas pembayaran gaji pegawai negeri.
